& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB) is a common and effective treatment of obesity. The development of an internal hernia after RYGB is the result of herniation of the small bowel through mesenteric defects created at the time of surgery. This can lead to further complications including recurrent abdominal pain and small bowel obstruction. In the most dire cases, closed-loop obstruction and/or volvulus can occur and lead to bowel ischemia and necrosis. Given the potentially severe complications of internal hernias after RYGB, it is incumbent on the radiologist to assess for them in all patients undergoing abdominal CT who have undergone RYGB, especially those presenting with abdominal pain. Detection of an internal hernia after RYGB at CT can be challenging. The authors discuss the postoperative anatomy after RYGB and the manner in which it can lead to internal hernias, the incidence of and risk factors for internal hernias, and the various signs at CT that can signal the presence of an internal hernia after RYGB.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2025</div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/large/rg.240197.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240197">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240197">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows the postoperative anatomy after antecolic RYGB. A small gastric pouch is created that bypasses most of the stomach. A Roux limb is anastomosed to the gastric pouch at the gastrojejunostomy. The bypassed biliopancreatic limb is anastomosed to the Roux limb at the jejunojejunostomy. The small bowel distal to the jejunojejunostomy is the common channel. The purple arrow demonstrates the path of ingested food. The green arrow demonstrates the drainage path of gastric, pancreatic, and biliary secretions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig1.jpg" height="1078" width="1080" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Illustration shows the postoperative anatomy after antecolic RYGB. A small gastric pouch is created that bypasses most of the stomach. A Roux limb is anastomosed to the gastric pouch at the gastrojejunostomy. The bypassed biliopancreatic limb is anastomosed to the Roux limb at the jejunojejunostomy. The small bowel distal to the jejunojejunostomy is the common channel. The purple arrow demonstrates the path of ingested food. The green arrow demonstrates the drainage path of gastric, pancreatic, and biliary secretions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustrations show the mesenteric defects responsible for internal hernias after RYGB. With both the antecolic (A) and retrocolic (B) approaches, Petersen and mesojejunal mesenteric defects associated with the Roux limb are created. A Petersen’s space (purple arrow, 1) is located between the cut edge of the Roux limb mesentery (red line) and the transverse mesocolon. The mesojejunal defect (green arrow, 2) is located between the cut edge of the biliopancreatic limb mesentery (blue line) and the adjacent Roux limb mesentery. The transmesocolic defect (pink arrow in B, 3) is only present with the retrocolic approach and is the defect created in the transverse mesocolon to tunnel the Roux limb through the transverse mesocolon to reach the stomach (green line in B)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig2.jpg" height="1047" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustrations show the mesenteric defects responsible for internal hernias after RYGB. With both the antecolic <b>(A)</b> and retrocolic <b>(B)</b> approaches, Petersen and mesojejunal mesenteric defects associated with the Roux limb are created. A Petersen’s space (purple arrow, <i>1</i>) is located between the cut edge of the Roux limb mesentery (red line) and the transverse mesocolon. The mesojejunal defect (green arrow, <i>2</i>) is located between the cut edge of the biliopancreatic limb mesentery (blue line) and the adjacent Roux limb mesentery. The transmesocolic defect (pink arrow in <b>B,</b><i> 3</i>) is only present with the retrocolic approach and is the defect created in the transverse mesocolon to tunnel the Roux limb through the transverse mesocolon to reach the stomach (green line in <b>B</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Laparoscopic view shows a Petersen’s space after reduction of a Petersen hernia. The space (dashed line) is bordered by the cut edge of the Roux limb mesentery (arrowheads) and the transverse mesocolon (black arrow). The transverse colon (open arrow) is marked for reference."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig3.jpg" height="990" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Laparoscopic view shows a Petersen’s space after reduction of a Petersen hernia. The space (dashed line) is bordered by the cut edge of the Roux limb mesentery (arrowheads) and the transverse mesocolon (black arrow). The transverse colon (open arrow) is marked for reference.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Laparoscopic view shows a mesojejunal defect after reduction of a mesojejunal hernia. The defect (dashed line) is bordered by the cut edge of the biliopancreatic limb mesentery (black arrow) and the Roux limb mesentery (white arrow). The laparoscopic probe (white arrowhead) traverses the mesojejunal defect. The Roux limb (open arrows) is marked for reference."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig4.jpg" height="1113" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Laparoscopic view shows a mesojejunal defect after reduction of a mesojejunal hernia. The defect (dashed line) is bordered by the cut edge of the biliopancreatic limb mesentery (black arrow) and the Roux limb mesentery (white arrow). The laparoscopic probe (white arrowhead) traverses the mesojejunal defect. The Roux limb (open arrows) is marked for reference.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Mesenteric swirl sign in a 35-year-old woman with a Petersen internal hernia 3 years after RYGB resulting in a 34-kg (32%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows swirling of the mesenteric vessels and proximal jejunum (white arrows) around the superior mesenteric artery (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig5.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Mesenteric swirl sign in a 35-year-old woman with a Petersen internal hernia 3 years after RYGB resulting in a 34-kg (32%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows swirling of the mesenteric vessels and proximal jejunum (white arrows) around the superior mesenteric artery (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Mesenteric swirl sign in a 45-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after RYGB. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows swirling of the mesenteric vessels and proximal jejunum (white arrows) around the superior mesenteric artery (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig6.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Mesenteric swirl sign in a 45-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after RYGB. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows swirling of the mesenteric vessels and proximal jejunum (white arrows) around the superior mesenteric artery (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="SMV compression sign in a 35-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 58-kg (44%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows focal narrowing of the SMV (white arrow), with distention of more peripheral SMV branches (red arrows). The central SMV is normal in caliber (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig7.jpg" height="716" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. SMV compression sign in a 35-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 58-kg (44%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows focal narrowing of the SMV (white arrow), with distention of more peripheral SMV branches (red arrows). The central SMV is normal in caliber (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="SMV compression sign in a 60-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 52-kg (44%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show focal narrowing of the SMV (arrow in A–C) with distention of more peripheral SMV branches (arrowheads in D)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig8.jpg" height="1202" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. SMV compression sign in a 60-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 52-kg (44%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show focal narrowing of the SMV (arrow in <b>A–C</b>) with distention of more peripheral SMV branches (arrowheads in <b>D</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Right-sided anastomosis in a 61-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after antecolic RYGB. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows the suture line of the jejunojejunal anastomosis in the right lower quadrant (white arrows). In addition, the image shows the SMV compression sign (red arrows). Sutures at the gastrojejunostomy are marked for reference (arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig9.jpg" height="900" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Right-sided anastomosis in a 61-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after antecolic RYGB. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows the suture line of the jejunojejunal anastomosis in the right lower quadrant (white arrows). In addition, the image shows the SMV compression sign (red arrows). Sutures at the gastrojejunostomy are marked for reference (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple signs of internal hernia after RYGB in a 42-year-old woman with a mesojejunal hernia 6 months after RYGB resulting in a 19-kg (19%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small bowel obstruction and several dilated bowel loops in the left upper quadrant (white arrowheads). There is a transition point in the central abdomen at the level of the hernia defect (red arrowhead). A C-shaped loop of bowel (white arrow) is a closed-loop component of the obstruction within the hernia. There is focal narrowing of an SMV branch at the level of the hernia (red ellipse). There is marked mesenteric edema (blue arrowheads). Multiple hypoenhancing and thickened segments of small bowel (red arrows) in the common channel were found to be ischemic at the time of surgery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig10.jpg" height="900" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Multiple signs of internal hernia after RYGB in a 42-year-old woman with a mesojejunal hernia 6 months after RYGB resulting in a 19-kg (19%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small bowel obstruction and several dilated bowel loops in the left upper quadrant (white arrowheads). There is a transition point in the central abdomen at the level of the hernia defect (red arrowhead). A C-shaped loop of bowel (white arrow) is a closed-loop component of the obstruction within the hernia. There is focal narrowing of an SMV branch at the level of the hernia (red ellipse). There is marked mesenteric edema (blue arrowheads). Multiple hypoenhancing and thickened segments of small bowel (red arrows) in the common channel were found to be ischemic at the time of surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Hooking intestine sign in a 48-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 14 months after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 56-kg (46%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show the Roux limb (red arrow in A and B) and the vessels in the Roux limb mesentery (white arrows in B–F) above (A, B), at (C), and below (D–F) the level of the transverse colon (white arrowheads in C). Vessels in the Roux limb mesentery pass anterior to two herniated small bowel segments in the Petersen’s space (red arrowheads in D) before returning to the central mesentery (E, F)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig11.jpg" height="1390" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Hooking intestine sign in a 48-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 14 months after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 56-kg (46%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show the Roux limb (red arrow in <b>A</b> and <b>B</b>) and the vessels in the Roux limb mesentery (white arrows in <b>B–F</b>) above <b>(A, B)</b>, at <b>(C)</b>, and below <b>(D–F)</b> the level of the transverse colon (white arrowheads in <b>C</b>). Vessels in the Roux limb mesentery pass anterior to two herniated small bowel segments in the Petersen’s space (red arrowheads in <b>D</b>) before returning to the central mesentery <b>(E, F)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Hooking intestine sign in a 46-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 5 months after RYGB resulting in a 23-kg (22%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows a hook-shaped configuration of the vasculature of the Roux limb mesentery (arrows). Two adjacent enteric contrast agent–filled loops of herniated small bowel (arrowheads) are present in the Petersen’s space inside the hook."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig12.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Hooking intestine sign in a 46-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 5 months after RYGB resulting in a 23-kg (22%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows a hook-shaped configuration of the vasculature of the Roux limb mesentery (arrows). Two adjacent enteric contrast agent–filled loops of herniated small bowel (arrowheads) are present in the Petersen’s space inside the hook.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes in a 45-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after RYGB. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows several prominent low- attenuation lymph nodes in the small bowel mesentery (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig13.jpg" height="534" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes in a 45-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 7 years after RYGB. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows several prominent low- attenuation lymph nodes in the small bowel mesentery (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Mesenteric edema sign (also known as weepy mesentery) in a 54-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 1 year after RYGB resulting in a 40-kg (36%) weight loss. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse edema in the small bowel mesentery (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig14.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Mesenteric edema sign (also known as weepy mesentery) in a 54-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 1 year after RYGB resulting in a 40-kg (36%) weight loss. Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse edema in the small bowel mesentery (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Eye of the hurricane sign in a 46-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 36-kg (24%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows a round appearance of the distal mesentery surrounded by small bowel loops (arrow). This appearance was present on several consecutive images."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig15.jpg" height="533" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Eye of the hurricane sign in a 46-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after RYGB resulting in a 36-kg (24%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows a round appearance of the distal mesentery surrounded by small bowel loops (arrow). This appearance was present on several consecutive images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Mushroom sign in a 53-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 59-kg (41%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows crowding and stretching of vessels near the mesenteric root (white arrows) as they pass between central mesenteric vessels (arrowhead) and distal mesenteric vessels (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig16.jpg" height="533" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Mushroom sign in a 53-year-old man with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 59-kg (41%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows crowding and stretching of vessels near the mesenteric root (white arrows) as they pass between central mesenteric vessels (arrowhead) and distal mesenteric vessels (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Mushroom sign in a 28-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 58-kg (41%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows crowding and stretching of vessels near the mesenteric root (arrows) as they pass between central (white arrowhead) and distal (red arrowhead) mesenteric vessels."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig17.jpg" height="565" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Mushroom sign in a 28-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 58-kg (41%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows crowding and stretching of vessels near the mesenteric root (arrows) as they pass between central (white arrowhead) and distal (red arrowhead) mesenteric vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel obstruction in a 50-year-old man with a mesojejunal hernia 1 year after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 55-kg (32%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple dilated small bowel loops (white arrows), with a focal transition point (red arrow) consistent with surgically proven small bowel obstruction caused by a mesojejunal hernia. The jejunojejunal anastomosis also is located to the right of midline (arrowheads)—an additional sign of an internal hernia after RYGB."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig18.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Small bowel obstruction in a 50-year-old man with a mesojejunal hernia 1 year after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 55-kg (32%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple dilated small bowel loops (white arrows), with a focal transition point (red arrow) consistent with surgically proven small bowel obstruction caused by a mesojejunal hernia. The jejunojejunal anastomosis also is located to the right of midline (arrowheads)—an additional sign of an internal hernia after RYGB.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel behind the SMA sign in a 44-year-old woman with a mesojejunal hernia 1 year after antecolic RYGB. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decompressed small bowel loop at the level of the jejunojejunal anastomosis (red arrow) behind the SMA (white arrow). Proximal to this point, the small bowel is dilated, which is consistent with small bowel obstruction (arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig19.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Small bowel behind the SMA sign in a 44-year-old woman with a mesojejunal hernia 1 year after antecolic RYGB. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decompressed small bowel loop at the level of the jejunojejunal anastomosis (red arrow) behind the SMA (white arrow). Proximal to this point, the small bowel is dilated, which is consistent with small bowel obstruction (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="Clustered small bowel loops in a 38-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 21-kg (26%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows clustered and crowded loops of bowel in the left upper quadrant (white arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig20.jpg" height="717" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Clustered small bowel loops in a 38-year-old woman with a Petersen hernia 2 years after antecolic RYGB resulting in a 21-kg (26%) weight loss. Axial intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT image shows clustered and crowded loops of bowel in the left upper quadrant (white arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel above the transverse mesocolon sign in a 54-year-old woman with a transmesocolic hernia 9 months after retrocolic RYGB resulting in a 39-kg (38%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show clustered loops of bowel (yellow shading) above the transverse colon (arrows in A). The middle colic vessels (arrowheads) wrap around the neck of the hernia at the defect in the transverse mesocolon with constriction of the mesentery (B) at this level."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240197/asset/images/rg.240197.fig21.jpg" height="841" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Small bowel above the transverse mesocolon sign in a 54-year-old woman with a transmesocolic hernia 9 months after retrocolic RYGB resulting in a 39-kg (38%) weight loss. Coronal intravenous and enteric contrast-enhanced CT images show clustered loops of bowel (yellow shading) above the transverse colon (arrows in <b>A</b>). The middle colic vessels (arrowheads) wrap around the neck of the hernia at the defect in the transverse mesocolon with constriction of the mesentery <b>(B)</b> at this level.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240197&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Alsuhibani A, Thompson JR, Wigle PR, et al. Metabolic and bariatric surgery utilization trends in the United States: evidence from 2012 to 2021 National Electronic Medical Records Network. <em>Ann Surg Open</em> 2023;4(4):e317.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/AS9.0000000000000317">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38144499/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Metabolic+and+bariatric+surgery+utilization+trends+in+the+United+States%3A+evidence+from+2012+to+2021+National+Electronic+Medical+Records+Network&amp;author=A+Alsuhibani&amp;author=JR+Thompson&amp;author=PR+Wigle&amp;publication_year=2023&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Open&amp;pages=e317&amp;doi=10.1097%2FAS9.0000000000000317&amp;pmid=38144499">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Iannelli A, Buratti MS, Novellas S, et al. Internal hernia as a complication of laparoscopic Roux-en-Y gastric bypass. <em>Obes Surg</em> 2007;17(10):1283–1286.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="ht